  "text": "TLS configuration flows through Prometheus from configuration files to actual HTTP clients via a multi-layer architecture spanning two repositories:\n\n## Configuration Definitions (prometheus/prometheus)\n\nIn prometheus/prometheus/config/config.go, both ScrapeConfig and RemoteWriteConfig embed the HTTPClientConfig from prometheus-common. These structs define the top-level configuration for scrape targets and remote write endpoints respectively. The HTTPClientConfig field is marked with YAML inline tag to allow direct configuration of HTTP client properties including TLS settings.\n\n## TLS Configuration Structures (prometheus-common)\n\nIn prometheus/common/config/http_config.go, the HTTPClientConfig struct contains a TLSConfig field. The TLSConfig struct defines the following TLS parameters:\n- CA certificates (via CA field for inline content or CAFile for file paths)\n- Client certificates and keys (CertFile, KeyFile, and inline Cert/Key fields)\n- Certificate references (CARef, CertRef, KeyRef for secret manager integration)\n- Server name verification (ServerName field for SNI)\n- Certificate validation control (InsecureSkipVerify flag)\n- TLS version constraints (MinVersion and MaxVersion)\n\nBoth HTTPClientConfig and TLSConfig include Validate() methods that enforce configuration constraints and file accessibility checks.\n\n## HTTP Client Creation for Scrape Targets (prometheus/prometheus)\n\nIn prometheus/prometheus/scrape/scrape.go, the newScrapeClient function takes an HTTPClientConfig parameter and delegates to config_util.NewClientFromConfig to create the HTTP client. This function receives the full ScrapeConfig's HTTPClientConfig, which includes all TLS settings.\n\n## HTTP Client Creation for Remote Write (prometheus/prometheus)\n\nIn prometheus/prometheus/storage/remote/client.go, the ClientConfig struct includes an HTTPClientConfig field. The NewWriteClient function similarly calls config_util.NewClientFromConfig with the client's HTTPClientConfig, passing the TLS settings from RemoteWriteConfig through to the configuration layer.\n\n## TLS Configuration Conversion (prometheus-common)\n\nIn prometheus/common/config/http_config.go, the actual conversion from Prometheus configuration to Go's standard tls.Config occurs through a chain of functions:\n\n1. NewClientFromConfig: Creates an HTTP client by building a configured round tripper\n2. NewRoundTripperFromConfig (wraps NewRoundTripperFromConfigWithContext): Creates the HTTP round tripper\n3. NewRoundTripperFromConfigWithContext: Validates the HTTPClientConfig and delegates TLS setup\n4. NewTLSConfig (wraps NewTLSConfigWithContext): Converts TLSConfig to tls.Config\n5. NewTLSConfigWithContext: The core implementation that:\n   - Loads root CA certificates from configured sources (inline CA, CAFile, or secret manager CARef)\n   - Retrieves and loads client certificates and keys\n   - Applies TLS version constraints (MinVersion/MaxVersion)\n   - Sets Server Name Indication (SNI) for hostname verification\n   - Configures certificate verification behavior based on InsecureSkipVerify\n   - Returns a fully configured *tls.Config object\n\n## Configuration Flow Summary\n\nThe complete flow is: YAML configuration → ScrapeConfig/RemoteWriteConfig → HTTPClientConfig → TLSConfig → NewClientFromConfig → NewRoundTripperFromConfigWithContext → NewTLSConfigWithContext → *tls.Config → HTTP client with TLS-enabled transport.\n\nThis architecture allows Prometheus to maintain centralized TLS configuration in prometheus-common that is consistently applied across all HTTP clients used for both scrape operations and remote write operations, supporting inline certificates, file-based certificates, and secret manager references."
}

